%description:
Disabling DAD should also suppress the global (SLAAC) DAD probe. [RFC 4862 5.1; NOT-MODELED]

RFC 4862 5.1 says a DupAddrDetectTransmits of zero disables Duplicate Address Detection for
*every* address the interface configures, not just the link-local one. INET honours this for
the link-local address (see Dad_Disabled) but still sends a DAD probe for the autoconfigured
global address, so the faithful "no DAD probe at all" assertion -- observed on the wire at
host1's interface -- is violated (an expected failure: the disable is applied inconsistently
across address types).

%file: Dad_DisabledGlobal.cc

#include "ProtocolTest.h"
#include "Ipv6TestSupport.h"

namespace inet {
namespace protocoltest {

Define_ProtocolTest(ipv6_dad_disabled_global)
{
    return ProtocolTest("ipv6_dad_disabled_global")
        .never(on("host1.eth[0].mac").signal("packetSentToLower")
                  .match([](const MatchContext& c) {
                      return isDadProbe(c.event) && nsTarget(c.event).isGlobal();
                  })
                  .describe("no global DAD probe may appear when DAD is disabled").within(4.0));
}

} // namespace protocoltest
} // namespace inet

%inifile: test.ini

[General]
*.tester.testName = "ipv6_dad_disabled_global"
include ../../ini/_base.ini

# Disable DAD everywhere.
**.ipv6.neighbourDiscovery.dupAddrDetectTransmits = 0

%expected-failure: DupAddrDetectTransmits=0 still probes the SLAAC global address (RFC 4862 5.1)

%contains: stdout
PROTOCOLTEST ipv6_dad_disabled_global: PASS
